\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb3 This page contains information about main validation strategies (schemes): 
\f2\b holdout
\f0\b0 , 
\f2\b K-Fold
\f0\b0 , 
\f2\b LOO
\f0\b0 .\cb1 \
\cb3 The main rule you should know \'97 
\f3\i never use data you train on to measure the quality of your model
\f0\i0 . The trick is to split all your data into 
\f3\i training
\f0\i0  and 
\f3\i validation
\f0\i0  parts. \cb1 \
\cb3 Below you will find several ways to validate a model.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f4\i\b \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 a) Holdout scheme:
\f0\i0\b0 \cb1 \ulnone \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1 \cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Split train data into two parts: \ul partA\ulnone  and \ul partB\ulnone .\cb1 \
\ls1\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Fit the model on \ul partA\ulnone , predict for \ul partB\ulnone .\cb1 \
\ls1\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Use predictions for \ul partB\ulnone  for estimating model quality. Find such hyper-parameters, that quality on \ul partB\ulnone  is maximized.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f0 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f4\i\b \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 b) K-Fold scheme:
\f0\i0\b0 \cb1 \ulnone \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1 \cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Split train data into K folds. \cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Iterate though each fold: retrain the model on all folds except current fold, predict for the current fold.\cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Use the predictions to calculate quality on each fold. Find such hyper-parameters, that quality on each fold is maximized. You can also estimate mean and variance of the loss. This is very helpful in order to understand significance of improvement.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f0 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f4\i\b \cf2 \cb3 \ul \ulc2 c) LOO (Leave-One-Out) scheme:
\f0\i0\b0 \cb1 \ulnone \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1 \cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Iterate over samples: retrain the model on all samples except current sample, predict for the current sample. You will need to retrain the model N times (if N is the number of samples in the dataset).\cb1 \
\ls3\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 In the end you will get LOO predictions for every sample in the trainset and can calculate loss.  \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f0 \cf2 \
\cb3 Notice, that these are 
\f3\i validation
\f0\i0  schemes are supposed to be used to estimate quality of the model. When you found the right hyper-parameters and want to get test predictions don't forget to retrain your model using all training data.\
